  <p class="article-lede">Ghana spends approximately $2 billion every year importing vegetable oils, mostly palm oil. It produces roughly 300,000 tonnes domestically against demand exceeding 500,000 tonnes. The government has launched a national programme targeting 100,000 new hectares and 250,000 jobs. On paper, this is one of the clearest import substitution opportunities in West Africa. In practice, the gap between policy ambition and plantation reality is measured in years, capital, and land disputes.</p>

  <p>This article scores the oil palm opportunity using GhanaWorld's weighted methodology, identifies the five barriers that separate the headline from the business case, and provides specific guidance for each audience type. Every figure is sourced and every risk is named.</p>

  <div class="data-box">
