  <h2 id="watch-next" style="margin-top:2rem;">What to Watch Next</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>National programme implementation data:</strong> Any verified hectarage figures from the government or independent monitoring would significantly change the opportunity score. Request through the Ministry of Food and Agriculture or the Tree Crops Development Authority.</li>
    <li><strong>Cocoa price trajectory:</strong> If cocoa remains below $4,000 per tonne through Q3 2026, farmer-level diversification pressure will accelerate, potentially creating a wave of oil palm planting (quality uncertain without seedling supply chain).</li>
    <li><strong>AfCFTA tariff negotiations:</strong> Any reduction in the 20% refined palm oil import tariff would undermine domestic competitiveness. Monitor Trade Ministry statements on agro-processing tariff lines.</li>
    <li><strong>DFI credit facilities:</strong> An IFC or AfDB facility specifically targeting Ghana oil palm would be a strong signal of institutional confidence in the sector's viability.</li>
    <li><strong>BOPP and GOPDC annual results:</strong> The most reliable source of actual yield, cost, and revenue data for oil palm operations in Ghana. Published on the GSE and in company annual reports.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 style="margin-top:2rem;">Source and Methodology Notes</h2>

  <p>Import gap figure based on Ghana trade data aggregates for vegetable oils. Production and demand estimates from industry sources and company reports (BOPP, GOPDC). National programme details from government policy announcements. Per-hectare economics derived from BOPP annual reports, GOPDC operational data, and West African agronomy literature. Opportunity scoring follows Section 47 of the GhanaWorld Constitution (weighted composite methodology). Cocoa price data from ICE futures. Macroeconomic indicators (GDP 6.0%, inflation 3.3%, policy rate 14%, GHS/USD 10.97) from Ghana Statistical Service and Bank of Ghana.</p>

  <p>Known Unknowns: National programme implementation status (hectares actually planted vs. announced). Smallholder adoption rates post-cocoa crisis. OPRI seedling production capacity and waitlist. Actual land dispute rates for agricultural leases in target regions. These are stated as gaps, not conclusions.</p>

  <p><em>Data freshness: All figures sourced as of 2026-03-29. Production and demand estimates tagged CURRENT (within 18 months). Per-hectare economics tagged CURRENT. Cocoa and macro data tagged FRESH. National programme status tagged UNVERIFIED. This analysis will be updated when verified planting data becomes available.</em></p>

